teristic forenames:  German Kurt.","Americanized form of German   Herrle  , which in the Franconian area means ‘grandfather’.","English and Irish: variant of   Harrell  ."]},{"name":"Hermann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Jurgen, Mathias, Gottlieb, Horst, Juergen, Klaus, Lorenz, Bernd, Dieter, Erwin.","German: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), Hungary, Poland, Czechia, Slovakia, and some other European countries; see also below. Compare   Harman   5.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): adoption of German name (see 1 above). Compare   Herman  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Herle was born about 1328, in Northumberland, England, United Kingdom, his mother, Margaret de Weyland, was 33 and his father, John De Herle I, was 32. He married Maud Thomas in 1355, in Northumberland, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1358, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 31."},"et":{"about 1328–1358":"umbes 1328–1358","1332–1358":"1332–1358","1354–1392":"1354–1392","1297–1417":"1297–1417","1297–1340":"1297–1340","1328–1358":"1328–1358","1358":"1358","about 1328":"umbes 1328","1355":"1355","1354":"1354","1332":"1332","1297":"1297","1340":"1340","1392":"1392","1417":"1417","1328":"1328","Devonshire, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":